{"title_page": "Alexander Home of North Berwick", "text_new": "'''Alexander Home of North Berwick''' (floruit 1570-1598) was a Scottish landowner and [[Provost of Edinburgh]].\n\nHis surname is sometimes spelled \"Hume\".\n\nHe was a son of Patrick Home of Polwarth (d. 1578) and Elizabeth Hepburn (d. 1571) daughter of Patrick Hepburn of [[Waughton Castle|Waughton]], and a younger brother of the courtier and poet [[Patrick Hume of Polwarth]] (d. 1599).\n\nHe obtained the lands of [[St. Mary's Priory (Lothian)|North Berwick priory]] from his younger sister Margaret Home, the last Prioress, in 1562.\n\nHe joined the court of [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] in 1580.\n\nHe was Provost of Edinburgh from 1593 to 1597, the leader of the town's council.\n\n On 3 April 1594 he fought in a battle at [[Leith]] against the rebel [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] using the town's artillery.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 305.</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 1594 Home was at [[North Berwick]] and received news that the rebel Earl of Bothwell and his companions were in Edinburgh and their horses were nearby at [[Dean Village|Dean Mills]]. Home returned and captured the horses and shut the town's gates, but failed to arrest the earl.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 369.</ref>\n\nIn January 1595 he captured [[James Scott of Balwearie]] an agent of the rebel earls.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 499, 510.</ref>\n\nHe was dead before October 1598 when a letter from the king about a shipping case mentions he was deceased.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 309.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home, Alexander}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alexander Home of North Berwick''' (floruit 1570-1598) was a Scottish landowner and [[Provost of Edinburgh]].\n\nHis surname is sometimes spelled \"Hume\".\n\nHe was a son of Patrick Home of Polwarth (d. 1578) and Elizabeth Hepburn (d. 1571) daughter of Patrick Hepburn of [[Waughton Castle|Waughton]], and a younger brother of the courtier and poet [[Patrick Hume of Polwarth]] (d. 1599).\n\nHe obtained the lands of [[St. Mary's Priory (Lothian)|North Berwick priory]] from his younger sister Margaret Home, the last Prioress, in 1562.\n\nHe joined the court of [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] in 1580.\n\nHe was Provost of Edinburgh from 1593 to 1597, the leader of the town's council.\n\n On 3 April 1594 he fought in a battle at [[Leith]] against the rebel [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] using the town's artillery.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 305.</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 1594 Home was at [[North Berwick]] and received news that the rebel Earl of Bothwell and his companions were in Edinburgh and their horses were nearby at [[Dean Village|Dean Mills]]. Home returned and captured the horses and shut the town's gates, but failed to arrest the earl.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 369.</ref>\n\nIn January 1595 he captured [[James Scott of Balweariew]] an agent of the rebel earls.<ref>Annie I. Cameron, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1593-1595'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 499, 510.</ref>\n\nHe was dead before October 1598 when a letter from the king about a shipping case mentions he was deceased.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 309.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home, Alexander}}\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Home_of_North_Berwick"}
